Bump version number

Update aacgm C library to version 2.4

Not an exact 1-to-1 copy because of mixed space/tab indenting in the
original source.

Procedure: First, diff'ed ignoring white space changes, then applied and
fixed some left-over space indents with tabs to match the original
(version 2.2) indenting.

In some places the code is still indented with two spaces instead of
tabs. We changed only the lines that were modified and kept the others
as they were.

Update py module setup to v2.4 aacgm sources

Version 2.4 of the aacgm C source brought in some extra files.
Adds those new files to setup.py to build the python module correctly.

aacgm: Set new environment variable IGRF_COEFFS

Version 2.4 now uses the environment  variable 'IGRF_COEFFS', so we
better set that as well. Not sure if we could remove 'IGRF_12_COEFFS'.

aacgm: Fix command line file output

Just passing argparse.FileType() resulted in empty output files when
used in np.savetxt(). Wrapping it in `with ... as f:` seems to mitigate
this issue and produces correct output files.

Update C submodule tests

Since of at least version 2.4, the returned radius is no longer equal to
one. Updates the test numbers to reflect that change and uses the
correct numbers for the tests.

Update py tests

Since of at least version 2.4, the returned radius is no longer equal to
one. Updates the test numbers to reflect that change and uses the
correct numbers for the tests for the python module functions.

Fix doctests in README and usage

Reformats the doctest outputs to match the actual outputs.
The numbers were correct but the slightly different spacing made the
doctests fail.

Fix doctests in README and usage (try #2)

The travis numpy output apparently differs from our local version.
Tries to fix the output by explicitly setting the numpy printoptions to
the common(?) lower precision.

Fix doctests in README and usage (try #3)

Moves `set_printoptions` directly before the output.

Fix doctests in README and usage (try #4)

Increases the printoptions precision to match the "old" number.
Updates the outputs to use the higher precision.

Fix doctests in README and usage (try #5)

Replace the simple variable output by formatted output.
Should circumvent the compatibility issues with numpy's variable
formats.

Fix doctests in README and usage (try #6)

Wraps the variables in `float()` because travis complains about

"Unknown format code 'f' for object of type 'str'"

for whatever reason.

Return the converted altitude as well

As of version 2.4 of the C aacgm library, the converted altitude
is supposed to be useful. We promote the returned altitude to the
python wrapper function so that people can use it if they want to.

Updates the function's inline documentation, the command line interface,
and the tests (standalone and doctests).

Fix file usage in command line interface

We wrapped the output nicely in a `with ... as f:` statement but forgot
to actually use f in `np.savetxt`.

CI: Remove python 3.3 testing environments

Travis.ci no longer supports python 3.3.

Fix tox/pytest warning about capturelog

Tox/pytest say that pytest-capturelog made it into the core and we
shouldn't depend explicitly on it anymore.

Silence pytest warning about configuration

Pytest looks now for a "tool:pytest" configuration entry instead of
just "pytest".

CI: Remove pytest-capturelog from tox.ini template

We removed the pytest-capturelog dependence from the generated tox.ini.
The template is probably a better place for this fix, so that our
changes are not overwritten when re-generating the configuration files.

CI: Skip codecov in travis template

While removing codecov from the generated config works, changing the
template will prevent the configuration from being overwritten on
re-generation.

Remove python 3.3 from setup.cfg matrix

Prevents re-generating the python 3.3 test and build environments.

Remove python 3.3 from appveyor config (generated)

Removing python 3.3 from setup.cfg removed the respective tox
environment entries from the generated appveyor configuration.

init: Fix PEP8

Working towards successful flake8 checks.

cli: Fix PEP8

Working towards successful flake8 checks.

setup.cfg: Ignore some flake8 errors

Ignores flake8 errors for successful checks.
Better ignore those errors than mess with the code too much.

Try to fix undefined math constants on Windows

M_PI is a POSIX extension which needs _USE_MATH_DEFINES to be defined
when including <math.h> on Windows. Detected by builds failing on
AppVeyor, hopefully fixing them.

(Some) References: robotology/QA#81
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1727881/how-to-use-the-pi-constant-in-c

MSVC fix: Implement setenv() and unsetenv()

On (AppVeyor's) MSVC, setenv() and unsetenv() are not defined.
Implements simple versions of those functions, based on AGB's variant,
slightly updated and re-formatted.

Puts the functions into a separate file to not mess with the original
code too much. That way, we only have to #include that file in rtime.c
when we include updates from the original C code.

Uses the solution [1] to properly emulate snprintf() on older
MSVC platforms.

Reference:
[1]https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2915672/snprintf-and-visual-studio-2010

MSVC fix: Define isfinite()

On (AppVeyor's) MSVC, isfinite() is not available.
Defines a macro which compares the value to NAN.

Based on AGB's macro, NAN should be already defined
when including math.h with _USE_MATH_DEFINES.

Python interface: Only warn and return NaNs

Instead of raising a RuntimeError, only issues a RuntimeWarning and
return NaNs when the called conversion function returns with an error.
This prevents `numpy.vectorize` from failing and the user can deal with
the returned NaNs.

Updates the tests accordingly.

ci: Enable "skip ci" on appveyor

Appveyor is stupid and looks for [skip ci] in the commit title only and
not in the whole message, so we have to search the message manually and
exit the builds manually.

References:
https://github.com/appveyor/ci/issues/1865
https://github.com/appveyor/ci/issues/1865#issuecomment-423091750

Rename module to avoid name clashes [1/3]

Trying to minimize the impact and the diff to the original sources by
just renaming the package and the python (main) module.

Seems to be much easier to rename the module directory than setting the
path explicitly in `setup.py` and seems more compatible with several
kinds of installation.
